712047f-a.text:
33rd Street, from Fifth to Sixth Avenues, inclusive, showing the Waldorf Hotel, built on the site of the residence of William Waldorf Astor. Around 1895 the adjoining house, the residence of John Jacob Astor, will be torn down and the Astoria built, the two hotels forming the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel.
About 1893.

Brown Brothers.

708498f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, west side, south from West 34th (right), to 33rd Streets, showing the Hotel Waldorf-Astoria. To the south, at the S.W. corner of 33rd Street (beneath the flag) is the Hotel Cambridge. Partially shown at the right margin is the former A. T. Stewart home,at this date the Manhattan Club. Astor Court, a short thru-way from 33rd to 34th Street is at the rear of the Hotel, and partially discernible there.
1898

Copyright 1898
J.S. Johnston, photo
Gift of Urbrock Collection

731196f-a.title: Celebrations - Parades - Municipal events - The Dewey Parade.
731196f-a.text:
Celebrations, Parades and Municipal Events: The Dewey Parade on Fifth Avenue, as viewed northward across 33rd Street. At the left is the Waldorf-Astoria hotel. Above same is the A.T. Stewart home; while farther to the north appears the spire of the Brick Presbyterian Church. The photographers vantage point is at the S.E. corner of Fifth Avenue and East 33rd Street.

J. J. Corell, photo
P. L. Sperr Collection

708506f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, west side, from West 33rd to 34th Streets, showing the demolition of the old Waldorf-Astoria Hotel. Upon this site will rise the towering Empire State Building. 33rd Street is to the left and 34th to the right. Upon the former appears an extensive view westward to Greeley Square with its tall Hotel McAlpin overlooking the subsequently
demolished (1939) Sixth Avenue "El" line.
The photographers vantage point is a structure at the S.E. corner of Fifth Avenue and 33rd Street and from which
he is viewing northwestward.
November 7, 1929

708507f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, west side, from West 33rd to 34th Streets, showing at this location the demolition of the old Waldorf-Astoria Hotel. This view taken in a southeastward direction shows the northerly (34th St.) side of this edifice. The photographers vantage point is a building on the north side of 34th Street, midway between Fifth and Sixth Avenues. Fifth Avenue and Astor Court are to the left and right respectively of the Hotel. The latter will disappear and be included in the site for the Empire State Building.
November 7, 1929

Fifth Ave. (left), west side, south from West 34th to Westt 33rd Streets. Also shown (right) is West 34th Street, south side, west from Fifth Ave. to Astor Court, showing the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel. This building was later demolished and on its site was erected in 1931, the Empire State Building. A new 47-story building was erected for the hotel on the east side of Park Ave., from East 49th to East 50th Streets and extending to Lexington Ave. The Waldorf-Astoria is New York's foremost hotel.
